Biogeographic transition zones are areas of overlap, located between two different biogeographic regions (Morrone 2006, 2015a; 

). Transition zones function as natural laboratories, since they present a gradient of replacement and segregation among biotic groups with different evolutionary origins (Morrone 2006, 2015a, 2020; 

). The following transition zones are recognized globally (

): Chinese (Palearctic-Oriental transition), Indo-Malayan (Oriental-Australian transition), Mexican (Nearctic-Neotropical transition), Saharo-Arabian (Palearctic-Ethiopian transition) and South American (Neotropical-Andean transition). The Mexican Transition Zone (MTZ) is recognized as a particularly complex area, since it hosts a wide variety of ecosystems, climates and orographic systems, as well as a high species richness and a considerable number of endemisms (

; 

, 2019, 2020; Halffter 2017, 2019; 

).

The first precedents for the MTZ are found in the works of 

, 

and Darlington (1957). However, it was 

who introduced a hypothesis to explain the geographic distribution of the insects from Mexico and the Americas. In 1964 Halffter reviewed his previous conclusions, and presented a first theory for the history of MTZ. According to this theory (

), the MTZ is a complex area of hybridization and overlap between the Nearctic and Neotropical regions, which extends from the southeastern United States to the Nicaraguan lowlands (
Fig. 1
). Since then, until recent years, the theory of the MTZ has been subsequently broadened (

, 

, 2017, 2019; 

, 

, 2019; 

). The most complete formal presentation of the theory of the MTZ is found in the works of 

, 2019, 2020) and 

, who compiled the ideas raised around Halffter’s initial proposal.

The classic explanation that separates the Nearctic and Neotropical regions with a border in Mesoamerica, often does not fit to the distribution and evolutionary history of the entomofauna in this region (

; 

, 

). Therefore, the current theory of the MTZ has been particularly useful to explain the biogeography of insects. 

, 

, 

, 

) initially used the term “dispersal patterns” to define those biological elements that formed the biogeographic scheme of the MTZ. Later, 

applied the term “distributional patterns”, since the biotic elements present in the MTZ are not determined exclusively by the phenomenon of dispersal, but also by vicariance. For this study we use “distributional pattern” to describe the current distribution of a cenocron within the MTZ. Therefore, distributional patterns here represent hypotheses regarding the current distribution and biogeographic history of the biota (Halffter 2017, 2019; 

; 

). Thus, distributional patterns are considered as hypotheses that can be tested by analytical methods, such as phylogenetic inference and ancestral areas reconstruction.

The distributional patterns in the MTZ have been characterized based on four elements: 1) the biogeographic origin [which in a broad sense can be Neotropical (
i.e.
, southern) or Holarctic (
i.e.
, northern)]; 2) the hypothetical age of dispersal towards the MTZ; 3) the geographic configuration of the MTZ when the phyletic lineages dispersed; and 4) the current distribution and ecological requirements of the taxa (Halffter 2017; 

). As a consequence, the lineages of insects of the MTZ that hypothetically originated from South American ancestors have been classified into four distributional patterns: Mexican Plateau, Mountain Mesoamerican, Neotropical Baja Californian and Typical Neotropical (

; 

; Morrone 2020). Moreover, the lineages of insects that radiated in the Old World and dispersed through North America to the MTZ are included within the Paleoamerican (with six sub-patterns, later described) and Nearctic distributional patterns (

; Morrone 2020).

First, we comment on the distributional patterns of southern origin. 1) Mexican Plateau distribution: This corresponds to the taxa that hypothetically dispersed to the Mexican Plateau during the Cretaceous and late Paleocene prior to the elevation of this geographic area. These taxa subsequently diversified and expanded to the southeastern United States of America and the highlands of Mesoamerica. These taxa prefer open or semi-open habitats with arid or semiarid conditions. It is thought that this is the most ancient Neotropical element of the MTZ (

, 

; 

). 2) Mountain Mesoamerican distribution: Taxa that dispersed from South America towards the Central American Nucleus during the Oligocene-Miocene, diversifying together with the tropical mountain cloud forests (

, 

; 

). 3) Neotropical Baja Californian distribution: Taxa of Neotropical origin endemic to the Baja California peninsula, which dispersed towards the peninsula during the Miocene prior to the appearance of the Gulf of California. They are typical of xerophytic coastal environments (

). 4) Typical Neotropical distribution: Taxa of South American origin, which hypothetically dispersed towards the MTZ during the Pliocene-Pleistocene, as part of the Great American Biotic Interchange (GABI). They are typical of lowlands and tropical environments present from South America to the coastal plains of the Gulf of Mexico, being particularly diverse in tropical rain forests (

, 

; 

).

Below, we list the distributional patterns of northern origin. The Paleoamerican pattern corresponds to Holarctic taxa that hypothetically arrived to North America from Eurasia during the early Cenozoic. These taxa are considered part of the most ancient biota of the MTZ (

; 

; 

) and are divided into six sub-patterns: 1) Relict Paleoamerican: Taxa with a wide distribution in the Old World, which are represented in the MTZ by a reduced number of endemic species with restricted areas of distribution; their distribution is explained as an extreme case of vicariance and subsequent retraction (

; 

; 

). 2) Mountain Paleoamerican: Taxa that successfully colonized the mountains of the MTZ and, to a lesser extent, those of Central America. These taxa have undergone an important process of diversification by vicariance, and are mainly adapted to cold and temperate climatic conditions, but some species may inhabit lowland areas adjacent to the mountains of the MTZ (

; 2019; 

; 

; 

). 3) Mexican Plateau Paleoamerican: Taxa that diversified on the Mexican High Plateau (

; Halffter 2017; 

). 4) Mesoamerican Paleoamerican: Taxa that diversified in the tropical mountain cloud forests of the Central American Nucleus (

; 

). 5) Paleoamerican Baja Californian: Taxa endemic to the xerophytic and coastal environments of the Baja California peninsula (

). 6) Tropical Paleoamerican: Taxa associated with the tropical and subtropical lowlands (

; 

; 

). The last four Paleoamerican sub-patterns are equivalent in terms of ecology and distribution to the patterns of Neotropical origin (

). Finally, the Nearctic distributional pattern includes taxa of Holarctic origin or endemic to North America, that dispersed towards the MTZ during the Miocene-Pliocene. These are restricted to cold and temperate zones (

, 

, 

; 

).

As stated above, the theory of the MTZ mainly explains the historical biogeography and current distribution of the insects. The 
Scarabaeinae
dung beetles have been the group most widely used for the conceptual development, since they exhibit all the distributional patterns, excepting the Nearctic one. The subfamily 
Scarabaeinae
(
Coleoptera
: 
Scarabaeidae
) comprises approximately 6580 species (

) and has an almost cosmopolitan distribution (

). Current evidence suggests that 
Scarabaeinae
are a monophyletic group (

; 

; 

; 

). This group of beetles feeds mainly on dung, but also exhibits saprophagous, necrophagous and, to a lesser extent, predatory habits (

, 

). The 
Scarabaeinae
contribute to the dynamics of ecosystems with key functions and services, such as cleansing of the ground surface, nutrient cycling, bioturbation and parasite control, among others (

; 

). Given the importance of the 
Scarabaeinae
to our understanding of the MTZ, our aim is to present an evolutionary scenario that allows us to infer the historical biogeography of the MTZ based on the phylogenetic interrelationships of this subfamily. In particular, we test how the taxa that makeup the distributional patterns of the MTZ integrated into an evolutionary, temporal and geographic scenario. Finally, the results obtained are compared with the conceptual framework provided by the theory of the MTZ.

We used four regions of the genome (COI, COII, 16S and ITS), increasing the probability of inferring the phylogeny of the taxa, instead of using only the history of one particular gene or organelle. We used the species 

Oscarinus indutilis
(Harold, 1874)

of the subfamily 
Aphodiinae
as the most basal out-group, because previous phylogenetic studies suggested that 
Aphodiinae
are the sister group of 
Scarabaeinae
(

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

). The complete list of species and the GenBank access numbers for each molecular marker are listed on 
Table 1
.

DNA was obtained from a small sample of tissue (2 or 3 legs in large individuals, pronotum in small individuals), which was cleaned and examined under the microscope in order to prevent any possible contamination by acari or fungi. The tissue was processed following the protocol of the DNeasy Blood & Tissue kit (QIAGEN). The COI gene was amplified with the primers NANCY (5’-cccggtaaaattaaaatataaacttc-3’) (

), HCO-2198 (5´-taaacttcagggtgaccaaaaaatca-3´) and LCO-1490 (5´-ggtcaacaaatcataaagatattgg-3´) (

). For 
COII
, we used the primers C1 (5´-ttgattttttggtcayccwgaagt-3´), 3014 (5´-ttcattgcactaatctgccatacta-3´), 3037 (5´- tagtatggcagattagtgcaatgaa-3´) and C2 (5´-ccrcaaatttcwgarcattgacca-3´) (

; 

). For 16S, we used the primers LR-J-12887 (5´-ccggtytgaactcaratca-3)´and LR-N-13398 (5´-crmctgtttawcaaaaacat-3´) (

; 

). 
ITS
2 was amplified with 
ITS
2A (5´-tgtgaactgcaggacacat-3´) and 
ITS
2B (5´-tatgcttaaattcagggggt-3´) (

).

Sequences were edited with Sequencher v5 (Gene Codes Corp, Ann Arbor, Michigan) and aligned with BioEdit v7.0.9 (

). The set of default options was used to produce the best alignment. Subsequently, this alignment was refined with MUSCLE v5 (Edgard 2004) and manually with Mesquite v3.1 (

). The phylogenetic hypothesis was recovered by Bayesian inference (BI) using MrBayes v3.2.3 (

). The best-fit nucleotide substitution model for each locus was selected using the Akaike information criterion (

) in jMODELTEST v2.0.2 (

). Monte Carlo Markovian Chains (MCMC) were implemented in two parallel analyses with four chains each (one cold and three hot). Twenty million generations were used for the combined data set. In each case, trees and parameters were sampled every 1000 generations. The majority-rule consensus tree was obtained, with the respective posterior probabilities (PP), after a burn-in discarding the initial 25% of the trees (

).

We dated the phylogeny using the software BEAST v1.10.2 (
), with the ‘Uncorrelated relaxed clock’ model. The BI topology inferred from the combined data set was used as a prior tree. For this study, the phylogeny was calibrated using the fossil record, considering 53 Myr as the minimum age for the whole subfamily
Scarabaeinae (Tarasov et al . 2016)
. A Bayesian factor test showed that the different molecular markers could be concatenated in a single matrix, but declared as independent partitions. Thus, the nucleotide substitution models were unlinked, as were the parameters used as priors for each locus. Models and parameters were those indicated by jMODELTEST. The Yule process was used to estimate the speciation tree model. The MCMC were run for 10 million generations, with sampling trees and parameters every 1000 generations. The analysis consisted of 10 independent runs to ensure that all parameters achieve statistical stationarity. The program TRACER v1.6 (
) was used for assessing the stationarity of the MCMC, effective sample sizes (ESSs> 200) and the 95% highest posterior density for interval spanning. The resulting trees and parameters from each run were combined using LogCombiner v1.8.2, applying a 25% burn-in of the initial data. The nodes evaluated for the final tree were those with PP value> 0.9.

An optimization analysis to infer the dispersal and vicariance events that occurred during the evolutionary history of the 
Scarabaeinae
in the MTZ was implemented in the software RASP 4 (

). To avoid the bias expected from the use of the outgroup, the species 

O. indutilis

was removed from the input trees. The ancestral state of each node was reconstructed in the condensed tree by using 5000 randomly selected trees from the remaining 60003 trees inferred after the 25% burn in in BEAST. The best-fit model for the ancestral area reconstruction was implemented with BioGeoBEARS (

, 

, 

). A highest AICc_wt value of 223.3 was retrieved from the BAYAREALIKE model. We assigned each taxon to the distributional patterns according to the MTZ theory. The reason to code the species with their distributional patterns and not with their individual distributional areas, is that these patterns can be considered as a reliable proxy for the current distributional areas of the cenocrons that assembled in the MTZ (

, 2020; Halffter 2017, 2019; 

). We must stress the fact that the objective of this study is to assess the general geographic patterns proposed by the theory of the MTZ for the biotic assemblages (
i.e.
, cenocrons), instead of the distribution of individual species. Unfortunately, in this study taxa from the Neotropical Baja Californian, Nearctic, Relict Paleoamerican and Paleoamerican Baja Californian cenocrons were omitted because we were unable to obtain sequences of their representative species. So far, the use of analytical methods to evaluate the theory of the MTZ, as well as our knowledge of the cenocrons that occur in the New World is still incipient. Consequently, the results and conclusions derived from this study are subjected to the current definition of the accepted cenocrons implemented here.

Undoubtedly, the biogeography of the 
Scarabaeinae
dung beetles from the MTZ (and the New World) represents an extremely complex scenario. Here, we integrated the information available for most of the distributional patterns that have been recognized in the MTZ. As the case of all the previous works dealing with the biogeography and evolutionary history of the 
