), our conclusions provide a provisional scenario based on the current knowledge and results, and are subject to new findings and subsequent analyses.

To better understand the evolutionary history and biogeographic processes that have shaped the diversity of Scarabaeinae , it would be desirable to increase the representation of geographic areas in future phylogenetic analyses. Our study is based on a regional subset of New World taxa that complements the global understanding of complex distributional patterns ( i.e. , African Scarabaeinae :
and
, and Australasian fauna:
). The genera
Onthophagus
, which is distributed in all continental-land masses (except for the Antarctica) and several islands (
), and
Copris
, which mainly occurs in Africa-Eurasia and the New World (
), represent two particular complex cases. These genera are widely distributed and highly diversified, which makes difficult adequately represent them in phylogenetic studies.

Two shortfalls that must be addressed in future studies are the reduced number of terminals included in the phylogenetic hypotheses, and the underrepresentation of taxonomic groups. With approximately 6580 
Scarabaeinae
species (

), the first point seems impossible to overcome in a short term. For example, 

