The origin of 
Scarabaeinae
is currently under debate with two competing hypotheses. On the one hand, a Mesozoic origin associated with the consumption of dinosaur dung (

; 

; 

, 

, 

; 

; 

, 

; 

). On the other hand, a Cenozoic one with subsequent diversification associated with mammalian dung (

, 

, 

; 

; 

; 

; 

). The dating of our phylogenetic reconstruction suggests an early Cenozoic origin for the 
Scarabaeinae
. Selection of the calibration point of our phylogeny was based on the study by Tarasov 
et al
. (2016), who revised all the known scarabaeine fossils and concluded that the oldest fossil 
Scarabaeinae
corresponds to 

Lobateuchus parisii
Montreuil, Génier & Nel, 2010

(Eocenic Oise amber of France, 53 Myr).

Previous studies (
;
;
) based their points of calibration on Cretaceous fossils ( i.e. ,
Prionocephale deplanate Lin, 1980
and
Juraclopus rohdendorfi Nikolajev, 2005
) that were erroneously attributed to Scarabaeinae or Scarabaeidae (
; Tarasov et al . 2016;
). Consequently, a Cretaceous origin for Scarabaeinae inferred from the use of these calibration points is not reliable. Certainly, the Scarabaeinae fossil record is extremely scarce and spatio-temporally restricted. Therefore, future discoveries will help improve the knowledge of the evolutionary history and biogeography of this insect group.

The association of 
Scarabaeinae
with the dung of large vertebrates from the Cretaceous (particularly dinosaurs) was originally proposed by 

and 

. This idea has been widely accepted by several authors (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

). Nevertheless, the hypothetical relationship between 
Scarabaeinae
and dinosaurs is mainly based on speculation and its original proposition was limited by the knowledge available several decades ago; however, it is not well supported by recent evidence. The ichnofossils associated with 
Scarabaeinae
have been fairly questioned (

; 

; 

; Tarasov 
et al
. 2016). 

reported that a dinosaur coprolite showed evidence of tunneling activity similar to those of 
Scarabaeinae
; nevertheless, 

concluded that at least some tunnels observed in dinosaur coprolites probably were produced by the activity of extinct cockroaches of the family 
Blattulidae
. It has been proposed that the chemical composition of dinosaur droppings was poorly suitable for 
Scarabaeinae
consumption, as a consequence of the combined voiding of fecal and high nitrate urinary products by the cloacal opening (

; 

). The presence of a cloacal opening in non-avian dinosaurs has been recently confirmed (

). Moreover, the consumption of highly nitrate droppings (such as those of birds and reptiles) by extant 
Scarabaeinae
seems to be extremely rare (

; 

), with ca. 80 records of 
Scarabaeinae
attracted to sauropsid dung (

) 
versus
at least 6850 extant dung beetle species (

). 

Canthon obliquus
Horn, 1894

, 

Copris gopheri
Hubbard, 1894

and 

Onthophagus polyphemi
Hubbard, 1894

are among the few cases of New World 
Scarabaeinae
successfully adapted to exploit the droppings produced by reptiles or birds (Young & Goff 1939; 

; 

; 

; 

).

Some previous phylogenetic hypotheses for Scarabaeinae dung beetles have suggested a Cenozoic origin for this subfamily (
;
), which is consistent with our results. Dating of these phylogenies was based on mutation rates and molecular-clock methods. A recent study that used molecular clock dating methods proposed a Mesozoic diversification for Scarabaeinae (
). Nevertheless,
suggested that the current fossil record for Scarabaeinae is not reliable, disregarding the seminal work on fossil Scarabaeinae by Tarasov et al . (2016).

Even if 
Scarabaeinae
dung beetles appeared during the Mesozoic, their evolution might be driven by the consumption of mammalian dung (

; 

). Indeed, the current knowledge points out that the mammalian crown group likely radiated during the Jurassic (

). Apparently, Mesozoic mammals were small body-sized and produced small droppings (

; 

), but this fact would not prevent the consumption of mammalian droppings by 
Scarabaeinae
(

). Indeed, several extant species are specialized on exploiting small dry dung pellets produced by mammals (

; 

, 

; 

; 

; 

, 2018; 

). It has been proposed that the ancestors of 
Scarabaeinae
likely were saprophagous beetles that shifted to coprophagy. Subsequently, the explosive radiation of mammals made available highly diversified dung sources that facilitated a rapid radiation in 
Scarabaeinae
(

; 

; 

). Saprophagy (

) or mycetophagy (

) have been proposed as the ancestral feeding preferences. Nonetheless, more studies are needed to test if the consumption of dung produced by mammals, reptiles or birds represents ancestral or derived character states in 
Scarabaeinae
beetles.

The phylogenetic reconstruction of the Scarabaeinae of the MTZ allowed us to explore the integration of the different distributional patterns in an evolutionary scenario. In general terms, the scenarios of dispersal and diversification proposed by previous authors (
,
,
,
, 2017;
,
, 2019;
) are not completely consistent with the reconstruction of ancestral stages presented in our study. According to our phylogenetic hypothesis, the only distributional patterns that completely agree with the temporal scenario as suggested by the previous literature are the Mountain Mesoamerican and Mesoamerican Paleoamerican, which appeared during the Miocene (
,
;
). The former includes lineages of Neotropical origin (e. g.,
