; 

, 

).

The appearance of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt completed the isolation of the Mexican Plateau that had begun with the formation of the Sierra Madre Oriental and Occidental mountains (

), which acted preventing the dispersal of Neotropical taxa while favoring that of Holarctic taxa (

; 

; 

; 

). Evidence of this phenomenon can be seen in the structure of the communities of 
Scarabaeinae
of the mountains of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt, where numerous species of Neotropical origin can be found in the zones of lower elevation in these mountains, but they decrease in abundance with increasing elevation until disappearing completely, being substituted by Holarctic elements in the high mountain zones (

, 

; 

; 

).

It is hypothesized that the Typical Neotropical distributional pattern represents a relatively recent dispersal event towards the MTZ and subsequent diversification, which took place together with the GABI during the Plio-Pleistocene (

, 

; 

). However, our results suggest that taxa previously considered as part of the Typical Neotropical distributional pattern diversified from multiple events of dispersal, which took place from the Oligocene to the Plio-Pleistocene.

The Ancient Neotropical distributional pattern represents a preliminary hypothesis that should be tested by subsequent studies. In this regard, the Ancient Neotropical pattern might include other cenocrons that our results were not able to recognize. So far, we cannot support a Gondwanan ancestry of the Neotropical 
Scarabaeinae
fauna (

, 

; 

; 

, 

; 

). Instead, 
Scarabaeinae
dung beetles might have originated mainly in the African continent during the early Cenozoic (

; 

; Cupello 
et al
. 2020; Cupello 2023). After the initial radiation, the Afrotropical ancestors of the Neotropical 
Scarabaeinae
might have dispersed from Africa to South America by transoceanic rafting (Cupello 
et al
. 2020; Cupello 2023). Additional cases of Neotropical biota that probably dispersed from Africa by transoceanic means have been established in mammals (Puox 
et al
