Previous authors have suggested that the Paleoamerican distribution corresponds to Holarctic taxa that dispersed towards North America during the upper Cretaceous to the Paleocene (

; 

; 

). Our results suggest that the Paleoamerican distribution originated during the late Oligocene, which is consistent with a previous study that suggests that the dispersal of 

Onthophagus

towards the New World took place since the late Oligocene until early Miocene (

). According to 

, the New World 

Onthophagus

probably arose in a single cladogenetic event from an Australian lineage that subsequently dispersed towards North America via Beringia. It appears that a land bridge connected western North America with eastern Asia on multiple occasions, from the mid-Cretaceous to the Pliocene, enabling biotic exchange between both continental masses (

; 

; 

). This makes plausible the phylogenetic hypotheses of 

and that presented by our study.

Our phylogenetic hypothesis suggests that the Tropical Paleoamerican represents the ancestral distribution of the New World 

Onthophagus

, from which originated the rest of the Paleoamerican elements. Two species of New World 

Onthophagus

were recently referred to as Typical Neotropical (

), but this was a mistake because both species must be considered as Tropical Paleoamerican. Previous authors (

; 

) have suggested that the term “Boreotropical distribution” should substitute that of Tropical Paleoamerican distribution, since they considered it a more complete and soundly based concept. The hypothesis of Boreotropical distribution suggests that a continuous strip of vegetation extended over the entire Northern hemisphere during the early Cenozoic, dispersing from Asia to North America through Beringia (

; 

). The subsequent climatic conditions of the terminal Eocene event caused the demise of the Boreotropical forest, as well as the subsequent isolation and vicariance of the organisms that inhabited this forest (

). In this way, a lineage that has its current center of diversity in tropical North America and appears in the fossil record during the early Paleocene, has a high probability of having sister groups in the Paleotropics and derived relatives in South America (

).

However, the hypothesis of Boreotropical distribution is not consistent with the evolutionary history of the New World 

Onthophagus

, taking into consideration the evidence provided by our results and those of previous studies: 1) As stated above, our phylogenetic hypothesis and that of 

suggest the appearance of the New World 

Onthophagus

during the late Oligocene, in a period much later than the dispersal and demise of the Boreotropical forest (

; 

). Moreover, paleoenvironmental reconstructions suggest the existence of tropical forests in the MTZ and northern South America during the Oligocene (

; 

; 

), while this 
type
of forest constitutes a suitable habitat for the Tropical Paleoamerican 

Onthophagus
(
Zunino & Halffter 1997
)

. 2) No fossil evidence is known that indicates the occurrence of 

Onthophagus

in North America during the early Tertiary. The only known fossils to date are traced back to the Pleistocene (Tarasov 
et al
. 2016; 

, 

). 3) The hypothetical sister group of the New World 

Onthophagus

is found outside of the Paleotropics, in Australia (

). 4) The center of diversity of the Tropical Paleoamerican 

Onthophagus

is found in the tropical rainforests of Central America and northern South America (

; 

), not in tropical North America (

). 5) Finally, 

supported his conclusions with the temporal calibrations provided by 

and 

; however, that is not reliable due to the fact that misidentified fossils were used for such calibrations. As a consequence, we can disregard the proposal by 

and 

, and retain the term Tropical Paleoamerican based on the evidence presented here.

The appearance of the Mexican Plateau Paleoamerican distribution was expected to be during the upper Cretaceous to early Cenozoic, prior to the elevation of the Mexican Plateau (

, 

; 

). Our results suggest that some Paleoamerican taxa dispersed towards the Mexican Plateau during the Miocene, while others did so during the Pleistocene. In either case, the Mexican Plateau Paleoamerican distribution arose from ancestors of Tropical Paleoamerican distribution. We can therefore suggest that the entomofauna of the Mexican Plateau were formed by at least two events of dispersal. The first event took place prior to completion of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt (

, 

), when the Holarctic and Neotropical 
Scarabaeinae
that inhabited the tropical lowlands of the MTZ dispersed freely towards the Mexican Plateau. It is possible to consider this dispersal event as the most important in terms of the formation of the entomofauna of the Mexican Plateau, since the lineages involved became isolated by the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt and subsequently dispersed to the southern United States of America, where they diversified (

; 

; 

). The second event of dispersal occurred after the formation of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt, during the Pleistocene. Given that only one species (
i.e.
, 

O. nitidior

) was assigned to this event, we suggest that it involved a very limited number of lineages of 
Scarabaeinae
that had the capacity to overcome the geographic barrier represented by the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt.

Previous authors suggested that the ancestors of the Mountain Paleoamerican distribution arose prior to the Miocene, since this period saw the formation of some of the main mountain chains of the MTZ (

; 

; 

). According to our phylogenetic reconstruction, the Mountain Paleoamerican sub-pattern appeared in at least two independent events of speciation during the Miocene, from ancestors of Tropical Paleoamerican distribution. During the Miocene, some mountain chains of the MTZ had a lower elevation, since an important part of the orogeny of the Sierra Madre Occidental developed in this period, as well as the beginning of the formation of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt (

, 

; 

). Moreover, the mid-Miocene Climatic Optimum caused the appearance of conditions of high temperatures and humidity in the MTZ (

; 

). Under this scenario, it is possible that the ancestors of Tropical Paleoamerican taxa colonized different mountainous zones, dispersing from the adjacent tropical lands, since the elevation and warm-humid climatic conditions did not constitute a limiting factor for their dispersal (

; 

).

Towards the end of the Miocene, the increased elevation of the large mountain chains of the MTZ (

, 

; 

), as well as the temperature decrease caused by the end of the mid-Miocene Climatic Optimum (

; 

), favored the isolation and subsequent diversification of the Paleoamerican lineages that could tolerate the changes in environmental conditions (

). The fossil record suggests that after the end of the mid-Miocene Climatic Optimum, different temperate mountain forests extended within the MTZ, comprising species of 

Pinus

L., 1753, 

Quercus

L., 1753, 

Juglans

L., 1753, and 

Ulmus

L., 1753; among others (

; 

). These forests are considered the main center of diversification of the Mountain Paleoamerican taxa (

, 

; 

). The scarcity of the Mountain Paleoamerican 
Scarabaeinae
in the temperate mountains of 
Chiapas
and Central America can be explained by the sinking of the Tehuantepec Isthmus, which created an area of tropical conditions at the end of the Miocene (

; 

) that acted impeding the dispersal of elements typical of the temperate mountains from 
Mexico
towards Central America (

).

Thanks to the phylogenetic reconstruction of the 
Scarabaeinae
of the MTZ and the paleogeographic scenario suggested by previous authors, we hypothesized that at least two transition zones existed between the Oligocene and Anthropocene between North and South America. We name these zones the Paleo-MTZ (Paleocene-Miocene) and current MTZ (Plio-Pleistocene; 
Fig. 4
). Halffter (2019) suggested the existence of at least two different transition zones in the space between North and South America, which are temporally successive but differ geographically and orographically. The main differences we recognize between both transition zones are the existence of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt and the Isthmus of Tehuantepec. The Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt is a Nearctic volcanic area of 1000 km in length that runs from the Pacific to the Atlantic Ocean, between the parallels 
18º 30’ N
and 
21º 30’ N
(

; 

). The Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt completed the volcanic arc that isolated the south of the Mexican Plateau (

; 

), preventing the dispersal of tropical taxa and allowing the dispersal and diversification of taxa of cold-temperate zones (

; 

). The Isthmus of Tehuantepec is a tropical lowland area located near the triple junction of the North American, Cocos and Caribbean tectonic plates (

). This isthmus prevented the dispersal of taxa of cold-temperate zones and favored the dispersal of tropical taxa (

; 

).

The main lineages of 
Scarabaeinae
of the MTZ arose during the Oligocene, giving origin to the Ancient Neotropical and Tropical Paleoamerican distributions. This period saw most of the orogeny of the Sierra Madre Occidental and the Sierra Madre del Sur, the elevation of the Mexican Plateau and the end of the formation of the Sierra Madre Oriental (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). Beringia and the North Atlantic Land Bridge connected North America to Eurasia, allowing dispersal of the Holarctic biota (

; 

), while Mexico was a peninsula that connected to South America through the proto-Antilles and the oceanic islands formed by the volcanic activity of the Central Panama Volcanic Field (

; 

; 

).

During the Oligocene, the Ancient Neotropical lineages were limited in terms of dispersal towards the PaleoMTZ, since in this stage only the “island hoppers” (
i.e.
, the Antillean Deltochilini genera that probably represent an ancient over-water dispersal) could successfully disperse from northern South America to southern Mexico(

; 

; 

). The tropical Holarctic elements (
i.e.
, 

Onthophagus

and 

Copris

) dispersed from Asia over land through Beringia (

). This dispersal probably took place at the end of the Oligocene, when the climatic conditions were more warm and humid (

). As a consequence, the Holarctic elements adapted to the tropical conditions found little limitation to their dispersal towards the Paleo-MTZ, in the geographic space currently occupied by the Mexican Plateau and to the lowlands of southeastern Mexico. During this period, it is probable that some Tropical Paleoamerican “island hoppers” began the dispersal from southern Mexico towards northern South America (as a matter of fact, the members of 

Onthophagus

are considered as successful over-water dispersers worldwide), by using the proto-Antilles and the volcanic islands of the Central Panama Volcanic Field as their principal routes of dispersal (

; 

; 

; 

).

The transformation of the Paleo-MTZ to the current MTZ probably began during the Miocene. This period saw the beginning or consolidation of some of the main current orographic systems, such as the Mexican Plateau, Sierra Madre Occidental, Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt and the Isthmus of Tehuantepec (

). Moreover, our results suggest that the greatest process of adaptive radiation of 
Scarabaeidae
occurred during the Miocene, giving origin to most of the distributional patterns (
i.e.
, the Mountain Mesoamerican, Mesoamerican Paleoamerican, Mountain Paleoamerican, Mexican Plateau, and Mexican Plateau Paleoamerican). This process of radiation could be the consequence of multiple factors: 1) The formation and consolidation of the orographic systems could have promoted the isolation of the 
Scarabaeinae
of the plateaus and mountains of the MTZ (

). 2) The mammalian megafauna of the Paleo-MTZ was present during the Miocene (

; 

), which could have ensured the availability of food and favored diversification of the 
Scarabaeinae
(

; 

; 

). 3) The large-scale generation of terrestrial landscapes occurred in Central America, favoring the connection between North and South America and facilitating dispersal of tropical taxa from northern South America (

; 

, 

). 4) The end of the mid-Miocene Climatic Optimum caused the beginning of a period of global cooling (

), which promoted the expansion of temperate biota in the MTZ (

; 

; 

; 

).

The current MTZ probably consolidated during the Pliocene. In this period, the connection between northern Europe and North America was lost (

). In addition, the orogenesis of the Sierra Madre Occidental was completed, while the arid scrublands and desert zones expanded in the Mexican Plateau and southeastern United States of America (

; 

; 

). The orogeny of the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt was consolidated and the mountainous belt around the Mexican Plateau was completed during this period (

; 

), preventing the dispersal of lowland tropical elements (

). The Central American Land Bridge probably became the main route of dispersal for the tropical elements, since the Panama Seaway probably started to consolidate during the Pliocene (

; 

, 

). Some ancient Holarctic elements of temperate and arid environments (
i.e.
, the 

Onthophagus chevrolati

and 

Onthophagus mexicanus

species groups) probably dispersed from the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt towards the Sierra Madre del Sur, where the Isthmus of Tehuantepec became the main geographic barrier to their dispersal (

). With the closure of the Panama Seaway, the marine connections between the Caribbean Sea and the Pacific Ocean were eliminated (

; 

).

During the Pleistocene, the connection between northern Asia and North America was lost (

). In this period, the mountains of the MTZ had already reached their current orographic configuration, forming geographic barriers that prevented the dispersal of tropical elements and those of the Mexican Plateau (

; 

; Halffter & Morrone 2010). The Isthmus of Tehuantepec reached its current formation, restricting the dispersal of Holarctic taxa (such as the 

O. chevrolati

species group) from the temperate mountains and the Mexican Plateau towards the south (

). This stage saw the demise of the mammalian megafauna and an increase in the aridity of the MTZ, which probably promoted the extinction of numerous species of 
Scarabaeinae
(e.g., 

Copris pristinus
Pierce, 1946

; 

Onthophagus everestae
Pierce, 1946

; 

Phanaeus labreae
(Pierce, 1946))

and reduced the species richness of their communities (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). Thanks to their long evolutionary history in tropical environments, the 
Scarabaeinae
dung beetles showed many trophic adaptations in the Neotropics, such as saprophagy, necrophagy and mycophagy, which allowed the persistence of highly diverse communities despite the loss of the mammalian megafauna (

; 

; 

; 

, 

; 

; 

).

We also suggest that the MTZ formed in two different stages: the Paleo-MTZ and the current MTZ. The Paleo-MTZ occurred between the Eocene and Miocene, when the main orographic systems of the region began or consolidated their formation, and all of the distributional patterns appeared. In the period of the current MTZ (from the Pliocene to the Anthropocene), all the orographic systems reached their current configuration, giving rise to the main biogeographic barriers: the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt for the biota of tropical affinity and the Isthmus of Tehuantepec for the biota of temperate environments. The evolutionary history of the 
Scarabaeinae
of the MTZ fits the “out of the tropics” model, in which taxa originated mainly in the tropics and expanded towards extratropical environments without losing their initial tropical distributions, while species movement was higher from the tropics to the extratropical areas (

; 

).
